1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,500
These pictures are tiny — book-page

2
00:00:02,500 --> 00:00:05,020
woodcuts you could hold in your hand, not

3
00:00:05,020 --> 00:00:07,700
the vast frescoes that once sprawled

4
00:00:07,700 --> 00:00:09,640
across the walls of medieval churchyards.

5
00:00:10,100 --> 00:00:12,280
For centuries they've been filed under a

6
00:00:12,280 --> 00:00:15,300
calm, dutiful label: a memento mori, a

7
00:00:15,300 --> 00:00:17,340
polite reminder that everyone, sooner or

8
00:00:17,340 --> 00:00:18,460
later, must die.

9
00:00:18,980 --> 00:00:21,120
And yet, hidden inside the sequence, there

10
00:00:21,120 --> 00:00:23,940
is a single image that quietly turns the

11
00:00:23,940 --> 00:00:26,720
whole thing inside out — that takes what

12
00:00:26,720 --> 00:00:29,160
looks like a sermon and reveals something

13
00:00:29,160 --> 00:00:30,420
far closer to a weapon.

14
00:00:30,660 --> 00:00:32,700
The series is called The Dance of Death.

15
00:00:33,300 --> 00:00:35,180
It was designed by Hans Holbein the

16
00:00:35,180 --> 00:00:39,120
Younger — who lived from 1497 to 1543

17
00:00:39,120 --> 00:00:41,500
— while he was working in Basel, somewhere

18
00:00:41,500 --> 00:00:44,360
between 1523 and 1526.

19
00:00:45,420 --> 00:00:47,660
Holbein drew the designs; the astonishing

20
00:00:47,660 --> 00:00:49,480
fineness of the cutting belongs to a

21
00:00:49,480 --> 00:00:51,520
master block-cutter named Hans

22
00:00:51,520 --> 00:00:54,400
Lützelburger, whose work has been called,

23
00:00:54,400 --> 00:00:57,160
quite simply, the most marvelous woodcuts

24
00:00:57,160 --> 00:00:57,980
ever made.

25
00:00:57,980 --> 00:01:00,600
By most accounts Lützelburger died around

26
00:01:00,600 --> 00:01:04,180
1526, before the book ever reached print —

27
00:01:04,180 --> 00:01:06,540
the craftsman who gave Death its face met

28
00:01:06,540 --> 00:01:07,240
Death first.

29
00:01:07,620 --> 00:01:09,620
The first edition appeared in Lyon in

30
00:01:09,620 --> 00:01:12,200
1538, published by the Trechsel brothers

31
00:01:12,200 --> 00:01:15,220
under a French title — Les Simulachres et

32
00:01:15,220 --> 00:01:18,400
Historiées Faces de la Mort, the images

33
00:01:18,400 --> 00:01:21,060
and storied faces of death — and it

34
00:01:21,060 --> 00:01:22,340
held forty-one woodcuts.

35
00:01:22,780 --> 00:01:24,540
People could not get enough of it.

36
00:01:24,540 --> 00:01:27,380
There were eleven editions before 1562,

37
00:01:27,840 --> 00:01:29,940
and across the century perhaps a hundred

38
00:01:29,940 --> 00:01:32,200
more unauthorized copies and imitations.

39
00:01:32,900 --> 00:01:35,060
An old churchyard tradition had been

40
00:01:35,060 --> 00:01:38,320
shrunk down, printed, and let loose across

41
00:01:38,320 --> 00:01:38,620
Europe.

42
00:01:38,764 --> 00:01:40,364
When you first leaf through the series,

43
00:01:40,824 --> 00:01:43,244
the premise looks simple, even repetitive.

44
00:01:43,704 --> 00:01:46,444
Into one ordinary moment after another — a

45
00:01:46,444 --> 00:01:48,664
throne room, a study, a day in the

46
00:01:48,664 --> 00:01:51,204
fields — strides the same uninvited guest:

47
00:01:51,624 --> 00:01:52,164
a skeleton.

48
00:01:52,604 --> 00:01:54,424
Death has come, and Death always wins.

49
00:01:54,844 --> 00:01:56,444
But look at how he behaves, and the

50
00:01:56,444 --> 00:01:57,724
simplicity falls away.

51
00:01:58,224 --> 00:02:00,224
Holbein's Death is not a solemn, hooded

52
00:02:00,224 --> 00:02:00,944
reaper.

53
00:02:01,244 --> 00:02:03,344
He is a performer, and the joke is

54
00:02:03,344 --> 00:02:04,904
always tailored to his victim.

55
00:02:04,904 --> 00:02:07,604
He turns into a kind of dispenser of

56
00:02:07,604 --> 00:02:10,284
justice — denouncing greed and the abuse

57
00:02:10,284 --> 00:02:10,844
of power.

58
00:02:11,364 --> 00:02:13,004
He robs the rich man of his money

59
00:02:13,004 --> 00:02:14,284
before he takes his soul.

60
00:02:14,624 --> 00:02:17,084
He boldly hauls an abbot away by his

61
00:02:17,084 --> 00:02:17,564
vestments.

62
00:02:17,784 --> 00:02:18,704
He skewers a knight.

63
00:02:18,964 --> 00:02:21,004
For the nobility, Death arrives as an

64
00:02:21,004 --> 00:02:23,404
opponent who simply cannot be beaten.

65
00:02:23,864 --> 00:02:25,944
In one scene after another, he doesn't

66
00:02:25,944 --> 00:02:28,404
merely take the powerful — he mocks the

67
00:02:28,404 --> 00:02:30,684
very thing they lived for, and more often

68
00:02:30,684 --> 00:02:32,724
than not he holds up an hourglass to

69
00:02:32,724 --> 00:02:33,144
do it.

70
00:02:33,944 --> 00:02:36,124
That little glass runs through the series

71
00:02:36,124 --> 00:02:36,924
like a refrain.

72
00:02:37,384 --> 00:02:39,604
And then he reaches the people who never

73
00:02:39,604 --> 00:02:41,984
had any power at all — and something

74
00:02:41,984 --> 00:02:43,924
strange happens to his manner.

75
00:02:44,145 --> 00:02:46,285
To feel why that matters, step back into

76
00:02:46,285 --> 00:02:47,565
the world that made these prints.

77
00:02:48,345 --> 00:02:50,665
The "dance of death," the danse macabre,

78
00:02:51,185 --> 00:02:53,805
was already an old idea — a procession

79
00:02:53,805 --> 00:02:55,305
of the living led away by the dead,

80
00:02:55,305 --> 00:02:57,925
painted across the walls of charnel houses

81
00:02:57,925 --> 00:03:00,125
so a whole town could file past it.

82
00:03:00,845 --> 00:03:02,765
Its message was blunt and democratic:

83
00:03:03,345 --> 00:03:05,325
whatever your rank, Death is the great

84
00:03:05,325 --> 00:03:08,165
equalizer, and every class distinction is

85
00:03:08,165 --> 00:03:11,085
wiped out the moment he takes your hand.

86
00:03:11,085 --> 00:03:13,465
Holbein inherited that idea — and

87
00:03:13,465 --> 00:03:15,045
sharpened every edge of it.

88
00:03:15,225 --> 00:03:17,485
He was working in Basel in the 1520s,

89
00:03:17,785 --> 00:03:19,465
a city right on the fault line of

90
00:03:19,465 --> 00:03:21,705
the Reformation, and what he made was less

91
00:03:21,705 --> 00:03:24,305
a gentle memorial than what scholars call

92
00:03:24,305 --> 00:03:27,185
a reformist satire: the old allegory,

93
00:03:27,465 --> 00:03:28,165
re-pointed.

94
00:03:28,484 --> 00:03:29,964
And now we come to the Ploughman.

95
00:03:30,604 --> 00:03:32,224
Among all these scenes of Death the

96
00:03:32,224 --> 00:03:34,664
tormentor — Death the thief, Death the

97
00:03:34,664 --> 00:03:37,144
mocker, Death who drags an abbot and

98
00:03:37,144 --> 00:03:39,764
unseats a king — there is one that

99
00:03:39,764 --> 00:03:41,464
is utterly different in tone.

100
00:03:41,804 --> 00:03:44,224
A peasant works his field behind a team

101
00:03:44,224 --> 00:03:46,164
of tired horses at the end of the

102
00:03:46,164 --> 00:03:46,364
day.

103
00:03:46,704 --> 00:03:48,684
And the figure beside him, helping to

104
00:03:48,684 --> 00:03:50,924
drive the horses on, helping him finish

105
00:03:50,924 --> 00:03:53,504
the very last furrow — that figure is

106
00:03:53,504 --> 00:03:53,804
Death.

107
00:03:54,184 --> 00:03:55,564
Here he is not a thief at all.

108
00:03:55,884 --> 00:03:56,584
He is a companion.

109
00:03:57,044 --> 00:03:59,264
He is almost a kindness, easing an

110
00:03:59,264 --> 00:04:01,324
exhausted man toward the end of his row,

111
00:04:01,544 --> 00:04:01,984
toward rest.

112
00:04:02,564 --> 00:04:03,644
Sit with the contrast.

113
00:04:04,324 --> 00:04:06,644
For the pope, the rich man, the knight,

114
00:04:06,644 --> 00:04:09,264
Death is an ambush and a humiliation.

115
00:04:09,804 --> 00:04:11,304
For the man who owns nothing but his

116
00:04:11,304 --> 00:04:12,704
labour, Death is mercy.

117
00:04:13,284 --> 00:04:15,304
The same skeleton, the same series, the

118
00:04:15,304 --> 00:04:17,284
same artist — and two opposite meanings,

119
00:04:17,644 --> 00:04:20,184
depending entirely on which rung of the

120
00:04:20,184 --> 00:04:21,764
ladder you happen to stand on.

121
00:04:22,118 --> 00:04:24,538
So which is the real Dance of Death?

122
00:04:24,758 --> 00:04:26,958
Here the interpretations split, and both

123
00:04:26,958 --> 00:04:27,518
have weight.

124
00:04:27,858 --> 00:04:30,058
The traditional reading is the gentle one.

125
00:04:30,298 --> 00:04:33,098
This is a memento mori: Death comes for

126
00:04:33,098 --> 00:04:35,378
everyone, pope and ploughman alike, so

127
00:04:35,378 --> 00:04:37,498
prepare your soul, because status counts

128
00:04:37,498 --> 00:04:38,878
for nothing in the end.

129
00:04:39,078 --> 00:04:42,038
Pious, universal, and perfectly at home in

130
00:04:42,038 --> 00:04:42,838
a prayer book.

131
00:04:43,138 --> 00:04:45,458
But notice who Death visits, and how.

132
00:04:45,838 --> 00:04:48,358
He marches the pope, the cardinal, the

133
00:04:48,358 --> 00:04:50,898
bishop, the abbot, the emperor and the

134
00:04:50,898 --> 00:04:53,118
king to the front of the procession, and

135
00:04:53,118 --> 00:04:55,498
he saves his cruelest jokes for exactly

136
00:04:55,498 --> 00:04:57,738
the people who claimed to stand above the

137
00:04:57,738 --> 00:04:59,118
crowd — and closest to God.

138
00:05:00,158 --> 00:05:02,598
Read that way, the series stops being a

139
00:05:02,598 --> 00:05:05,098
soft reminder of mortality and becomes a

140
00:05:05,098 --> 00:05:07,198
reckoning: Death as the one honest

141
00:05:07,198 --> 00:05:09,918
official who cannot be bribed, flattered,

142
00:05:10,138 --> 00:05:11,078
or outranked.

143
00:05:11,338 --> 00:05:12,818
And yet — and this is where it

144
00:05:12,818 --> 00:05:15,398
stays honest — Holbein doesn't simply hate

145
00:05:15,398 --> 00:05:15,998
the Church.

146
00:05:16,238 --> 00:05:18,118
Look closely and you'll find that the

147
00:05:18,118 --> 00:05:20,178
humble preacher and the parish priest

148
00:05:20,178 --> 00:05:23,098
escape his sarcasm entirely; they're shown

149
00:05:23,098 --> 00:05:24,538
in sympathy with the poor.

150
00:05:25,118 --> 00:05:27,118
His scorn isn't aimed at faith.

151
00:05:27,498 --> 00:05:28,418
It's aimed at power.

152
00:05:28,649 --> 00:05:31,609
That, perhaps, is the real trick of these

153
00:05:31,609 --> 00:05:32,169
little pictures.

154
00:05:32,909 --> 00:05:34,689
The very same book could sit on a

155
00:05:34,689 --> 00:05:37,009
bishop's shelf as a devout meditation and

156
00:05:37,009 --> 00:05:39,709
circulate among reformers as a joke at the

157
00:05:39,709 --> 00:05:40,429
bishop's expense.

158
00:05:41,009 --> 00:05:43,929
The piety is the disguise; the protest is

159
00:05:43,929 --> 00:05:46,669
the payload — and both are completely true

160
00:05:46,669 --> 00:05:47,249
at once.

161
00:05:47,889 --> 00:05:49,429
Holbein understood that the most

162
00:05:49,429 --> 00:05:51,609
unsettling thing you can show the powerful

163
00:05:51,609 --> 00:05:53,129
is not that they will die.

164
00:05:53,469 --> 00:05:54,269
They knew that.

165
00:05:54,529 --> 00:05:56,169
It's that when they die, they will be

166
00:05:56,169 --> 00:05:58,749
exactly equal to the peasant in the field

167
00:05:58,749 --> 00:06:00,909
— and that the peasant, of the two,

168
00:06:00,909 --> 00:06:03,249
may be the one who finally gets to

169
00:06:03,249 --> 00:06:03,569
rest.

170
00:06:03,797 --> 00:06:05,277
So I'll hand the question to you.

171
00:06:06,257 --> 00:06:08,297
When you look at Holbein's skeleton —

172
00:06:08,297 --> 00:06:09,957
dragging the pope from his throne, and

173
00:06:09,957 --> 00:06:11,997
helping the ploughman home — do you see

174
00:06:11,997 --> 00:06:14,337
a preacher reminding us all of our end?

175
00:06:14,977 --> 00:06:17,377
Or a satirist, smuggling a quiet

176
00:06:17,377 --> 00:06:18,937
revolution inside a prayer book?

177
00:06:19,817 --> 00:06:20,757
Tell me how you read it.

178
00:06:21,497 --> 00:06:23,257
Thank you for looking this closely with

179
00:06:23,257 --> 00:06:23,437
me.
